@ram.rom82,
The funny thing is that I have always looked at it the other way around.  Keep that beautiful body, but replace the old-fashioned engine and transmission with the modern stuff.  Cars in those days were ofter worn out long before 100,000 miles.  You got an engine overhall at about 50 or 60 thousand, and a completly new engine at about 80 thousand.  Unfortunately, by then the other mechanical stuff was in bad shape too, so a new engine wasn't always practical.

Later this week, I am leaving for Florida, from Tennessee, in a 10-year-old Toyota with 190,000 miles on it.  I'm not really worried about it.  Thank goodness, they don't make 'em the way they used to.  But I loved the way they looked.
